div.div:
A pattern of filters that re-occurs as particularly useful across data sets (applying the pattern interface) or has a 'reason' why it's useful (it separates data that tends to have a common pattern which responds to this separation in a useful way, or it separates data in a way that quickly filters data sets that happen to be common) is a useful structure to identify as a possible useful default structure, to fulfill queries like 'find a filter to reduce the solution set' without generating & filtering possible filters, and instead using the default useful filter.
For example, a 'reason' the pictured filters might be generally useful is that they leave only a little space after they're applied, so they might be generally useful for finding 'smaller structures with fewer nodes' that could fit in that space.
If this info is present as an input (it's already know the structure to be identified will likely be smaller), this filter structure could be applied by default, as it's known to be useful for finding smaller structures.
